<p>[About ekw theme] | [ekw Scheme Cannery] (trade settings with your friends)
</p>

<p>Colors can be any valid HTML color: Either hex triplets 
(<tt><b>#<font color="#c00000">RR</font><font color="#008000">GG</font><font color="#0000c0">BB</font></b></tt>) 
or named colors (e.g. <tt><span duh_style="font-weight: bold; background-color: papayawhip;">papayawhip</span></tt>). 
See [% linkNode( getNode( 'Named HTML Colors', 'superdoc' ) ) %] for some information that's actually useful. 
[% linkNode( getNode( 'E2 Color Toy', 'superdocnolinks' ) ) %] will help translate normal numbers into HTML colors, and it 
will also generate gradients from one color to another. 

</p>

<p>Font information is expressed in [Cascading Style Sheets|CSS] 
terms: 12 pixels is expressed as "<tt>12px</tt>", 12 points is 
expressed as "<tt>12p<b>t</b></tt>". You can also do percentages. 
Percentages of <em>what</em>? Damned if I know! Font names are 
comma-separated lists, such as "<tt>Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif</tt>", 
where the browser tries to find the first one, then moves on down 
the list until it finds one that's installed on your computer.
</p>

[%
if ( $query->param( 'restore_defaults' ) || $query->param( 'canned' ) ) {
    # Remove old ekw settings.
    for my $key ( keys %$VARS ) {
        if ( $key =~ /^ekw_/ ) {
            delete $$VARS{ $key };
        }
    }

    if ( defined $query->param( 'canned' ) ) {
        my $SCHEMENODE = getNode( 'ekw canned schemes', 'setting' );
        my $SCHEMES    = getVars( $SCHEMENODE );

        my $scheme = $$SCHEMES{ $query->param( 'canned' ) };

        if ( $scheme ) {
            local *repl_cb = sub {
                my ( $name, $value ) = @_;
                if ( $name =~ /^(text|bg|alink|oddrow|logoborder|logomaintext|vlink|logoaccenttext|link|logobackground|logo|text|heading|mono)(color|size|font){0,2}$/ ) {
                    $$VARS{ 'ekw_' . $name } = $value;
                }
            };
            # Maybe instead of rejecting values that are too 
            # long, we should accept anything and then truncate 
            # when we stick it in $VARS in the callback.
            $scheme =~ s/ekw_([a-z]+)=\"([a-zA-Z0-9 ,#\.\-]{1,96})\";/repl_cb($1,$2)/ge;
        } else {
            return "<p><b>'$scheme' is not a valid scheme identifier.</b></p>";
        }
    }
}

'';
%]

